  "text": "The Rust compiler and Servo browser engine share code through the stylo CSS styling engine, which is maintained in the separate servo/stylo repository. Servo depends on the stylo crates via git dependencies at commit 9a413b4d05d899c3baedd7b648dbf2c23dc9b879.\n\n## Servo Style System\n\nIn servo/servo, the Cargo.toml file declares dependencies on external crates from the servo/stylo repository:\n- selectors crate (servo/stylo:selectors/Cargo.toml) declares dependencies on: cssparser (0.36), rustc-hash (2.1.1), phf (0.13), servo_arc, smallvec (1.0), and to_shmem\n- stylo crate (servo/stylo:style/Cargo.toml, library name \"style\") declares dependencies on: selectors, servo_arc, cssparser (0.36), euclid, and many others including encoding_rs, string_cache, and url\n\nThe main entry point for the style system is servo/stylo:style/lib.rs, which documents that the main entry point is the `recalc_style_at` function in the traversal module. Major dependencies documented in the crate are cssparser and selectors.\n\n## Rust Compiler and Servo Relationship\n\nSearching through the rust-lang/rust compiler and library crates revealed NO direct dependencies on or imports from Servo's selectors crate. The two projects remain separate and do not share code at the compiler level.\n\n## Proc_Macro Bridge\n\nThe proc_macro bridge that enables build scripts is located in rust-lang/rust at library/proc_macro/src/bridge/. Key files include:\n\n- library/proc_macro/src/bridge/mod.rs: Defines the `with_api!` macro which describes the server RPC API for proc_macro communication. This is the core specification of the bridge protocol that separates client (proc macro crate) and server (compiler front-end) communication using serialization and unique integer handles.\n\n- library/proc_macro/src/bridge/client.rs: Client-side implementation\n\n- library/proc_macro/src/bridge/server.rs: Server-side implementation\n\n- library/proc_macro/src/lib.rs: Main library entry point that exposes the public `proc_macro::bridge` module\n\nThe `with_api!` macro defines RPC methods for TokenStream operations (drop, clone, is_empty, expand_expr, from_str, to_string, etc.), Span operations (debug, parent, source, byte_range, line, column, file, etc.), Symbol operations, and environment/path tracking. The bridge::client module's `is_available()` function is used to detect whether the proc_macro infrastructure is available."
}

